While it often feels futile, I was dutifully checking the pines on the west side of the driving range when suddenly a GHOW flushed from near the top of one of the pines. It landed in a bare tree just a bit to the west, where it was immediately harassed by a pair of Cooper's Hawks. Within a few minutes, one of the Coops chased the GHOW all the way across the driving range to the east, where the GHOW eventually chose a tree by the batting cage in which to rest. As if that wasn't enough, the GHOW was then relentlessly harassed by a RTHA. It resettled at least one more time before eventually hunkering down in another tree where it continued to be pestered by crows. I felt so bad for accidentally flushing this bird after seeing it get pestered so relentlessly. Fortunately it wasn't too bothered and even stayed for (at least) one more night on Randalls.

Media notes: Three young Great Horned Owls sitting on the rail of my parent's old house.
Observation Details: Three newly-fledged young perched on the rail of my parent's old house and just a few feet from ours. They have been in the community for a few days now. They just sit around or make short moves to new locations and seem unbothered by people or noise. Their occasional sharp screeches continue well into the night if not all night long. This is the 3rd or 4th year in a row we have had a family of Great Horned Owls right in the community, out in the open just as those are.

Observation Details: This bird probably jumped/fell from its nest sometime between Monday and Wednesday. It was seen last night by several people, and demonstrated lots of defensive behavior. It's a bit small for a fledgling, but not unexpected for an early brancher. I've had about three years of bird rehab experience so I biked over in the snow to check on the chick. It had managed to clamber up on a log, which was good, but it acted very lethargic. It barely clacked its bill three times when I came up to it and mostly slumped on the log. Its outer feathers were rather wet from the snow and rain, and it sat hunched up. It was holding a well-chewed pinecone in its claw. Tried to eat it? I usually stay far away from owls, but I came closer than normal to check its activity and health. No pellets were seen near it. I sent photos to a rehabber who said that the chick isn't abnormally young for fledging. Their advice was to wait and see what happens. The Cornell undergrads will be checking on it every day or so. There's at least one coyote in the vicinity, because we found some very fresh and chewed bones with a DOG shock collar tangled in them last Friday. Hopefully the bird will be ok!

Observation Details: Have seen almost every time I ventured during the Winter, not sure if still using now that it's almost Summer, although I wouldn't doubt it. If you park at Morton field complex, walkdown old farm road ( think that's the name, the trail that had the Barred owl roosting in the Sycamore tree). Walk down that road till you get to where the meadow starts. Take a left onto Meadows edge trail. Take the next left onto Woodlands trail, then the right at the fork ( Chartiers floodplains trail?). Walk on trail as it gradually moves down the hill into the lower forested area. Keep walking down and will be in right location if you see some Rusty old poles ( light poles?). When you see the poles make a right, and then the next right onto the next trail. If you follow this trail it should lead you to chartiers creek. You will see what appears to be an island ( not an island though) it will have a little inlet on it's left,  if you look to the center of this "island" there is a huge sycamore tree. Look up you should be able to see this cavity clear as day. Sorry about the directions lol but you should be able to spot it pretty easily once you know where to look. Good luck!

*More infrequent in Dobbs than in Hastings and this area is the only spot I know of with prior records. My first Dobbs record. Having said that, Dobbs has incredible habitat to support many more GHOWs. Exceptional find by Tom Warren and many thanks to him for alerting me about this bird. Certainly an odd bird: despite the throngs of large, old, and dense spruce, hemlock, and pine in the vicinity, this bird chose to perch in a short, open pine right next to the trail (amazing for views — it was impossible for me to be within less than 15-20ft of the bird based on its position — but a horrible tree for the owls purpose). Without a doubt the fastest I’ve ever found a GHOW; I just arrived in the area  and instantly found it preening. Likely a female based on size but I’m not entirely sure. Oddly enough in an area of the OCA that I scour intently for owls year-round without success (granted I’ve been looking in the owl-appropriate trees, not the glorified bush this bird was in 😂). Soon after I arrived, a walker managed to somehow flush this bird which had been passed by people all day. Incredible to watch the bird take off and land about 150ft away in an oak. I watched it at a distance for awhile before finally leaving. Once again, Tom THANK YOU!!

Observation Details: Roosting in a tree along the top hedgerow, only a few feet above the ground.  I was starting to get cold and figured that I had seen most of the sparrows in the area, so turned around to trudge through the snow, into the wind, and head back towards my car. However, right when I started to turn back I noticed the shape of a large owl perched low on a distant hedgerow. To my surprise, a beautiful Great Horned Owl was tucked-up and sleeping in the sun! I slowly made my way closer, constantly checking that the owl was still asleep. Once I was within 100 feet, I crawled over closer and tried to stay hidden in the grass. The owl remained still, with its eye closed tight. After a few minutes it did slowly open its eyes, and looked at me and stood up a little taller, but after a minute or two it fell back to sleep and I snuck away.
Second time that I have had one at this location, first one this spring.

Many observers.  Adult owl perched in open and mobbed by crows.  The adult owl reacted just like what you expect from a great horned owl; soon as it sees a human, it takes off.  The owl flew over a hundred yards and then across the road. The juvenile from this year was perched nearby in the open.   Very cooperative and didn't react to all the photographers standing around.  I think there is a chance the juvenile may stay into at least early October.  I am not as familiar with the dispersal pattern of this species but have read that they tend to disperse from the natal area in the fall.  On the otherhand, I know way too much about the eastern screech owl :-)

Observation Details: Well this was quite an adventure.  I spotted this bird on the ground in Greenridge Cemetery which didn't seem right.  I didn't want to approach too closely so circled around.  It stayed in the same spot only moving its head.  I continued my walk but passed through a while later on my way home.  I thought it was gone and went to the spot only to find I was almost on top of it.  It had moved a couple feet under a bush.  Ironically it was by several of my ancestor's graves...haha.  I called Fellow Mortals and they called me back mid day and told me how I could capture and box it.    When I went back to the cemetery it was not in that spot but some cemetery workers had seen it and directed me to it.  It had moved maybe 50 yards.  I managed to capture it and get it in a box...still can hardly believe it...and then I took it out to Fellow Mortals.  They evaluated it with some neurological symptoms but generally good health otherwise.  They marked it as having a fair prognosis.  Just have to hope for the best.

Snyder's (scalariventris)

2 scalariventris ("Snyder's) (one individual was missing a portion of its left ear tuft); 1 heterocnemis ("Labrador") individual. The first four photos are Snyder's Great Horned Owl. This is a pale northern subspecies of the Great Horned Owl, whose range is almost entirely in northern Ontario, except in winter when some come south. Its facial discs are pale grey and its plumage is much paler than the typical Great Horned Owl of southern Ontario. This subspecies was described in 1961 by L.L. Snyder of the Royal Ontario Museum who named the breeding population in northern Ontario as Bubo virginianus scalariventris. The last two photos are of Labrador Great Horned Owl, a dark subspecies of Great Horned Owl, Bubo virginianus heterocnemis, breeds in northern Quebec, Labrador, and Newfoundland and wanders occasionally in winter into Ontario. Its facial discs are dark and its plumage is darker that the typical Great Horned Owl of southern Ontario.

Have seen almost every time I ventured during the Winter, not sure if still using now that it's almost Summer, although I wouldn't doubt it. If you park at Morton field complex, walkdown old farm road ( think that's the name, the trail that had the Barred owl roosting in the Sycamore tree). Walk down that road till you get to where the meadow starts. Take a left onto Meadows edge trail. Take the next left onto Woodlands trail, then the right at the fork ( Chartiers floodplains trail?). Walk on trail as it gradually moves down the hill into the lower forested area. Keep walking down and will be in right location if you see some Rusty old poles ( light poles?). When you see the poles make a right, and then the next right onto the next trail. If you follow this trail it should lead you to chartiers creek. You will see what appears to be an island ( not an island though) it will have a little inlet on it's left,  if you look to the center of this "island" there is a huge sycamore tree. Look up you should be able to see this cavity clear as day. Sorry about the directions lol but you should be able to spot it pretty easily once you know where to look. Good luck!

Have seen almost every time I ventured during the Winter, not sure if still using now that it's almost Summer, although I wouldn't doubt it. If you park at Morton field complex, walkdown old farm road ( think that's the name, the trail that had the Barred owl roosting in the Sycamore tree). Walk down that road till you get to where the meadow starts. Take a left onto Meadows edge trail. Take the next left onto Woodlands trail, then the right at the fork ( Chartiers floodplains trail?). Walk on trail as it gradually moves down the hill into the lower forested area. Keep walking down and will be in right location if you see some Rusty old poles ( light poles?). When you see the poles make a right, and then the next right onto the next trail. If you follow this trail it should lead you to chartiers creek. You will see what appears to be an island ( not an island though) it will have a little inlet on it's left,  if you look to the center of this "island" there is a huge sycamore tree. Look up you should be able to see this cavity clear as day. Sorry about the directions lol but you should be able to spot it pretty easily once you know where to look. Good luck!

While it often feels futile, I was dutifully checking the pines on the west side of the driving range when suddenly a GHOW flushed from near the top of one of the pines. It landed in a bare tree just a bit to the west, where it was immediately harassed by a pair of Cooper's Hawks. Within a few minutes, one of the Coops chased the GHOW all the way across the driving range to the east, where the GHOW eventually chose a tree by the batting cage in which to rest. As if that wasn't enough, the GHOW was then relentlessly harassed by a RTHA. It resettled at least one more time before eventually hunkering down in another tree where it continued to be pestered by crows. I felt so bad for accidentally flushing this bird after seeing it get pestered so relentlessly. Fortunately it wasn't too bothered and even stayed for (at least) one more night on Randalls.

The first specimen was hidden in a tree close to the main forest trail. I spotted its heat signature using thermal imaging before making visual ID. I was able to take several photos from different angles. It did not seem to mind my presence as long as I kept a reasonable distance. It flew to a nearby tree branch, and then behind some dense vegetation.  I returned to the location 10-15 minutes later (after checking out a nearby area) and spotted (likely) the same specimen close to the ground using thermal (it was almost pitch black outside, about 30 mins after sunset). Another owl flew and landed near it, up in a tree - this one appeared smaller in size. After a while, the specimen on the ground started vocalizing at low volume.

Media notes: Female stretching.
Observation Details: When we arrived, the male was ensconced in the many-and-skinny-limbed tree, and the female was perched in a favorite cottonwood some forty yards to the east.  The female stretched and preened and yawned.  They hooted to each other a few times.  The male flew to the old magpie nest on the north side of Bear Creek.  The female flew to one of her favorite hunting perches, remaining on the south side of the creek. The male hooted a few times from within the magpie nest, but the female did not respond.  The male then flew to a favored perch west of the pond that never freezes, and hooted some more.  Still, the female did not respond.  He flew off.  Back on her hunting perch, the female was fixated on nearby brush.  At 5:20 p.m., she flew down to the brush, caught a vole, and then flew to the closest branch to where three of us were standing.  She spent a few minutes eating, and then carried the vole off to the east.

Media notes: Great Horned Owl seen near sunset
Observation Details: This is the first GHOW i have ever seen (outside an aviary). The owl was sitting upright in a deciduous tree about 10' up from the ground. It looked a  little bigger than a Barred owl, but smaller than a GGOW. It had 2 tufts, "ears", on top of its head. They were orangey-rusty at the base, black in front. The owl had yellow eyes, a round face, wide white rings around its eyes, rusty patches on the upper outer edges of the eyes, a black ring around the face disc, and a thin white V from the tufts to the dark gray hooked bill. Under the chin it had a white patch that appeared to be in a V shape, like bib. Its "moustaches" were white and grey speckled.  There was fine brown wavy barring on a white chest and belly, browns and gray with white speckles on wings and back. It had white  under the tail. There are brown bands on the tail and the terminal band was white. The pattern on the head made it look like tightly curled wool. Overall the bird looked (a slightly grayish) brown with white markings. I only got a brief glimpse of one foot when the bird changed position. It appeared to have white feathers down to the toes with black claws. It was not like the 2 larger owls have seen in the wild. A Barred owl has dark eyes, no tufts, a yellow bill and vertical bars. A Great Gray has a white "moustache", an all white face disc, no tufts and a different brown, besides being bigger.

Assuming an average incubation period of 33 days, the eggs would have hatched around March 10, making the oldest chick about 6 weeks old. At 6 weeks nestlings start to move around onto nearby branches which seems to match what was observed today. (Source: birdsoftheworld.org).

Observation Details: *More infrequent in Dobbs than in Hastings and this area is the only spot I know of with prior records. My first Dobbs record. Having said that, Dobbs has incredible habitat to support many more GHOWs. Exceptional find by Tom Warren and many thanks to him for alerting me about this bird. Certainly an odd bird: despite the throngs of large, old, and dense spruce, hemlock, and pine in the vicinity, this bird chose to perch in a short, open pine right next to the trail (amazing for views — it was impossible for me to be within less than 15-20ft of the bird based on its position — but a horrible tree for the owls purpose). Without a doubt the fastest I’ve ever found a GHOW; I just arrived in the area  and instantly found it preening. Likely a female based on size but I’m not entirely sure. Oddly enough in an area of the OCA that I scour intently for owls year-round without success (granted I’ve been looking in the owl-appropriate trees, not the glorified bush this bird was in 😂). Soon after I arrived, a walker managed to somehow flush this bird which had been passed by people all day. Incredible to watch the bird take off and land about 150ft away in an oak. I watched it at a distance for awhile before finally leaving. Once again, Tom THANK YOU!!

2 scalariventris ("Snyder's) (one individual was missing a portion of its left ear tuft); 1 heterocnemis ("Labrador") individual. The first four photos are Snyder's Great Horned Owl. This is a pale northern subspecies of the Great Horned Owl, whose range is almost entirely in northern Ontario, except in winter when some come south. Its facial discs are pale grey and its plumage is much paler than the typical Great Horned Owl of southern Ontario. This subspecies was described in 1961 by L.L. Snyder of the Royal Ontario Museum who named the breeding population in northern Ontario as Bubo virginianus scalariventris. The last two photos are of Labrador Great Horned Owl, a dark subspecies of Great Horned Owl, Bubo virginianus heterocnemis, breeds in northern Quebec, Labrador, and Newfoundland and wanders occasionally in winter into Ontario. Its facial discs are dark and its plumage is darker that the typical Great Horned Owl of southern Ontario.

Observation Details: Roosting in a tree along the top hedgerow, only a few feet above the ground.  I was starting to get cold and figured that I had seen most of the sparrows in the area, so turned around to trudge through the snow, into the wind, and head back towards my car. However, right when I started to turn back I noticed the shape of a large owl perched low on a distant hedgerow. To my surprise, a beautiful Great Horned Owl was tucked-up and sleeping in the sun! I slowly made my way closer, constantly checking that the owl was still asleep. Once I was within 100 feet, I crawled over closer and tried to stay hidden in the grass. The owl remained still, with its eye closed tight. After a few minutes it did slowly open its eyes, and looked at me and stood up a little taller, but after a minute or two it fell back to sleep and I snuck away.
He was in the same area when I viewed him 2 weeks ago.

The owlets were inquisitive, looking around at every noise (including me at some points!) and other people walking along the trail and dogs barking in the distance. Mostly groggy when first seen, but upon visiting again at the end of the day (and watching them beyond after I stopped this checklist) they became much more active as night set in. Mom eventually flew out of the nest to go hunting.

Many observers.  Adult owl perched in open and mobbed by crows.  The adult owl reacted just like what you expect from a great horned owl; soon as it sees a human, it takes off.  The owl flew over a hundred yards and then across the road. The juvenile from this year was perched nearby in the open.   Very cooperative and didn't react to all the photographers standing around.  I think there is a chance the juvenile may stay into at least early October.  I am not as familiar with the dispersal pattern of this species but have read that they tend to disperse from the natal area in the fall.  On the otherhand, I know way too much about the eastern screech owl :-)

Well this was quite an adventure.  I spotted this bird on the ground in Greenridge Cemetery which didn't seem right.  I didn't want to approach too closely so circled around.  It stayed in the same spot only moving its head.  I continued my walk but passed through a while later on my way home.  I thought it was gone and went to the spot only to find I was almost on top of it.  It had moved a couple feet under a bush.  Ironically it was by several of my ancestor's graves...haha.  I called Fellow Mortals and they called me back mid day and told me how I could capture and box it.    When I went back to the cemetery it was not in that spot but some cemetery workers had seen it and directed me to it.  It had moved maybe 50 yards.  I managed to capture it and get it in a box...still can hardly believe it...and then I took it out to Fellow Mortals.  They evaluated it with some neurological symptoms but generally good health otherwise.  They marked it as having a fair prognosis.  Just have to hope for the best.

I heard the scratchy calls of a juvenile GHO. I located one adult and one juvenile in a densely leafy tree. There might have been more than two hiding in that tree, but I only saw two. I made two recordings of the juvenile GHO calls. Merlin suggested that a Barn Owl was also present. I have seen Barn Owls many times at Lk_Yos, but I have yet to hear one make any sound. I didn’t hear anything on my recordings that persuaded me that Barn Owl was real. When I uploaded my two recordings to BirdNET, the program assigned the maximum score of 1.00 to GHO and scores of 0.22 and 0.06 to Barn Owl. I cannot rule out Barn Owl, but I think it's more likely that Merlin and BirdNET confused the GHO begging call for the similar-sounding Barn Owl call.

Locality: Bear Creek Greenbelt--S Kipling Pkwy to S Wadsworth Blvd
Observation Details: When we arrived, the male and female Great Horned Owls were sitting side-by-side in the many-and-skinny-limbed tree.  Nearly an hour later, at 4:38 p.m., they performed their first duet.  Twenty minutes later, at 4:58 p.m., they performed their second.  Then the male hooted at 5:00 p.m., 5:01 p.m., and 5:03 p.m., with no response.  Just before 5:04 p.m., they dueted three times, then the male flew off to the north.  At 5:09 p.m. the female flew off to the south.  At 5:12 p.m. we found the male sitting by the old magpie nest.  He hooted.  She didn't respond.  At 5:14 p.m. he flew to a tall tree to the north, and hooted again.  She didn't respond.

Observation Details: I finally figured out what kind of owl lives in the trail. I've seen this owl 4 or 5 times just this spring and I haven't been able to get a good enough look to see what species it was.  I was always wondering why there was no barred owl in the trail, I thought it would be the perfect spot due to the diverse amount of prey in the area (5 species of turtles, 6 species of frogs/toads 4 species of snakes and 1 species of river snake, trout stocked river, crayfish, racoons, skunks, foxes, squirrels, mice, chipmunks, minks, groundhogs and all the diverse species of birds that I find here and many more animals I'm probably forgetting I saw in this trail) The fact that this owl was a great horned basically means no other owl will want to live here, since every owl is on the prey list for these guys.

Media notes: Have seen almost every time I ventured during the Winter, not sure if still using now that it's almost Summer, although I wouldn't doubt it. If you park at Morton field complex, walkdown old farm road ( think that's the name, the trail that had the Barred owl roosting in the Sycamore tree). Walk down that road till you get to where the meadow starts. Take a left onto Meadows edge trail. Take the next left onto Woodlands trail, then the right at the fork ( Chartiers floodplains trail?). Walk on trail as it gradually moves down the hill into the lower forested area. Keep walking down and will be in right location if you see some Rusty old poles ( light poles?). When you see the poles make a right, and then the next right onto the next trail. If you follow this trail it should lead you to chartiers creek. You will see what appears to be an island ( not an island though) it will have a little inlet on it's left,  if you look to the center of this "island" there is a huge sycamore tree. Look up you should be able to see this cavity clear as day. Sorry about the directions lol but you should be able to spot it pretty easily once you know where to look. Good luck!

2 scalariventris ("Snyder's) (one individual was missing a portion of its left ear tuft); 1 heterocnemis ("Labrador") individual. The first four photos are Snyder's Great Horned Owl. This is a pale northern subspecies of the Great Horned Owl, whose range is almost entirely in northern Ontario, except in winter when some come south. Its facial discs are pale grey and its plumage is much paler than the typical Great Horned Owl of southern Ontario. This subspecies was described in 1961 by L.L. Snyder of the Royal Ontario Museum who named the breeding population in northern Ontario as Bubo virginianus scalariventris. The last two photos are of Labrador Great Horned Owl, a dark subspecies of Great Horned Owl, Bubo virginianus heterocnemis, breeds in northern Quebec, Labrador, and Newfoundland and wanders occasionally in winter into Ontario. Its facial discs are dark and its plumage is darker that the typical Great Horned Owl of southern Ontario.

Observation Details: Continuing female with her young. There are two owlets!! Only one was seen yesterday, the first day I saw any in the nest. Today, the female was seen preening her owlets and the owlets were seen stretching their wings and moving around the nest. The owlets were inquisitive, looking around at every noise (including me at some points!) and other people walking along the trail and dogs barking in the distance. Mostly groggy when first seen, but upon visiting again at the end of the day (and watching them beyond after I stopped this checklist) they became much more active as night set in. Mom eventually flew out of the nest to go hunting.

Observation Details: Seen in riparian woodland to the south of the Columbia River levee in the last 50 yards of woods as you walk toward the fish ladders. I followed it as it moved about 5 times. It always perched at about twice to three times my height on horizontal limbs. It never moved far and did allow careful indirect approach, but never directly toward. Was successful at angling slightly away from it and slowly turning for the shot multiple times.  NOTE: This GHO has a damaged eye. It appears to me that it has taken a strike in its left eye that has damaged its yellow iris. At first I thought the bird might have a concussion and uneven pupil size, but upon observing the jagged yellow iris, I'm coming down on the poke damage side. I have notified Audubon.

Found sitting on the ground by Goose Run, this bird appeared to be unwell; it was not alarmed by our approach, didn't track us visually as we moved around, and didn't seem to hear us.  Upon closer look the right eye was obviously compromised.  After talking to a wildlife rehabber we attempted to capture the bird; to our surprise it flew across the creek where it sat for a couple of minutes on a rock, then flew a bit further down the creek, without incident.  It perched on a branch over the creek, pooped, ruffled its feathers, and surveyed its surrounding before flying further down the creek again, still pretty much ignoring us.  While obviously not acting "normally" it is not on its last legs at the moment, so we left it in peace with our best wishes.

Although Great Horned Owls are fairly common in the washes and neighborhood here in Anthem, we have never had one perch on our backyard view fence while it was still light.  There was a very nervous bunny cowering under the Sweet Acacia tree, hoping that the owl did not see it.  The owl, however, was more concerned about me, as I snapped pictures of it.  It finally got tired of the photo session, started to rapidly spin its head around, coughed up a large pellet, and flew off.  What a show!
